    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1961-11-09T16:36:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1961-11-09T16:36:00-05:00" n="232"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d232">
                <head>232. Notes of a Meeting, Department of State<note n="1" type="source"
                        xml:id="d232fn1">Source: National Defense University, Lemnitzer Papers,
                        L-216-71. Secret. Handwritten by <persName corresp="#p_LGLL1"
                            >Lemnitzer</persName>. According to the source text, the following
                        people were present at the meeting: <persName corresp="#p_RD1"
                            >Rusk</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_MNRS1">McNamara</persName>,
                            <persName corresp="#p_GRL1">Gilpatric</persName>, <persName
                            corresp="#p_NPH1">Nitze</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_LGLL1"
                            >Lemnitzer</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_BWP1">William
                            Bundy</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_HWA1">Harriman</persName>,
                            <persName corresp="#p_BGW1">Ball</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_JUA1"
                            >U. Alexis Johnson</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_TGMD1"
                            >Taylor</persName>, and <persName corresp="#p_RWW1">Rostow</persName>.
                        According to <persName corresp="#p_RD1">Rusk</persName>’s Appointment Book,
                        he met at 4:36 p.m. on November 9 to discuss Viet-Nam with <persName
                            corresp="#p_BGW1">Ball</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_MNRS1"
                            >McNamara</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_GRL1">Gilpatric</persName>,
                            <persName corresp="#p_LGLL1">Lemnitzer</persName>, <persName
                            corresp="#p_RWW1">Rostow</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_NPH1"
                            >Nitze</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_TGMD1">Taylor</persName>,
                            <persName corresp="#p_BWP1">William Bundy</persName>, and <persName
                            corresp="#p_JUA1">U. Alexis Johnson</persName>. <persName
                            corresp="#p_HWA1">Harriman</persName> joined the meeting at 5:06 p.m.
                        The next appointment shown was a 6:41 p.m. meeting with <persName
                            corresp="#p_MNRS1">McNamara</persName> alone. (Johnson Library, Rusk
                        Appointment Books)</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <hi rend="italic">
                            <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                                when="1961-11-09T16:36:00-05:00">November 9, 1961, 4:36 p.m.</date>
                        </hi>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Sec. State read p. 1<note n="2" xml:id="d232fn2">Reference is apparently to the
                        draft paper described in <ref target="#d228fn1">footnote 1, Document
                            228</ref>.</note> aloud. Argument on “extremely.” <persName
                        corresp="#p_RD1">Rusk</persName> questioned “sharply against,” par. 3 &amp;
                    4.</p>
                <p>I raised question of what is the obj.</p>
                <p>Secy. Def. would put his first par. 1st p. 8.</p>
                <p>I objected to parenthetical remarks. I stated that we must have a clear statement
                    of the milt objective before we rec[ommend] a force to accomplish it.</p>
                <pb facs="0595" n="573" xml:id="pg_573"/>
                <p>Sec. State insisted on discussing troop deployment rather than face real issue of
                    troops.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_RWW1">Rostow</persName> believes it would be easier to get
                        <gloss target="#t_SEATO1">SEATO</gloss> into the 17th area rather than in
                    the plateau area.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_RD1">Rusk</persName> leans strongly toward introducing
                    administrators, <gloss target="#t_MAAG1">MAAG</gloss>, etc.—it does not commit
                    US as does combat forces. Reluctant to put in US forces until Diem makes a 100%
                    effort in his area. Cited US pulling out students, etc., while <gloss
                        target="#t_VN1">VN</gloss> students stay in school. What domestic case can
                    be made for such a step?</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_HWA1">Harriman</persName>—pare 5 line 8—suggests we have a
                    conference before we put forces in-would confront …<note n="3" xml:id="d232fn3"
                        >Ellipsis in the source text.</note>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_RWW1">Rostow</persName>—<persName corresp="#p_DMJ1"
                        >Desai</persName> says that if you try to deal with <gloss target="#t_ICC1"
                        >ICC</gloss> before troops you have no bargaining power.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_HWA1">Harriman</persName> believes we should have a
                    showdown with plan ready. If you put in troops there is no real negotiation
                    possible with Russians.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_NPH1">Nitze</persName> believes introduction of US forces
                    will result in stepping up infiltration.</p>
                <p>Sec. State-to <persName corresp="#p_HWA1">Harriman</persName>: Will putting US
                    forces in <gloss target="#t_VN1">VN</gloss> blow open Laotian situation?</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_HWA1">Harriman</persName>—Yes. World does not consider
                    that <gloss target="#t_VC1">VC</gloss> are supported from North-they believe it
                    is Diem’s fault. Time schedule-release Jorden report. Talks with USSR within a
                    few days.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_RD1">Rusk</persName>-national interest obj. What we should
                    do. Scenario-diplomatic moves.</p>
            </div>
